The paper discusses the historical significance of research in machine translation, which falls under the category of natural language processing (NLP). Therefore, cs.CL (Computation and Language) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses the approach to machine translation advocated by the Croatian group, which is different from the usual logical approaches of the period, and his advocacy of cybernetic methods, which would be adopted as a canon by the mainstream AI community only decades later. Therefore, cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) is also a likely sub-category. The paper also mentions the legacy of the machine translation program in establishing a Croatian machine translation program based around the Faculty of Humanities and Social Sciences of the University of Zagreb, which involves human-computer interaction and user-centered design, making cs.HC (Human-Computer Interaction) a possible sub-category. The paper also discusses the cybernetic methods advocated by the Croatian group, which involves machine learning and optimization, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions the intelligence needs of the period, which involves decision-making and optimization, making cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing) a possible sub-category.
